items.abstract:
<jats:title>Abstract</jats:title>
            <jats:p>Let <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> be a finite group with an abelian normal subgroup <jats:italic>N</jats:italic>. When does <jats:italic>N</jats:italic> have a unique conjugacy class of complements in <jats:italic>G</jats:italic>? We consider this question with a focus on properties of maximal subgroups. As corollaries we obtain Theorems 1.6 and 1.7 which are closely related to a result by Parker and Rowley on supplements of a nilpotent normal subgroup [3, Theorem 1]. Furthermore, we consider families of maximal subgroups of <jats:italic>G</jats:italic> closed under conjugation whose intersection equals <jats:inline-formula id="j_jgth-2017-0033_ineq_9999">
                  <jats:alternatives>
                     
                     <jats:inline-graphic xlink:href="graphic/j_jgth-2017-0033_eq_mi304.png" />
                     <jats:tex-math>{\Phi(G)}</jats:tex-math>
                  </jats:alternatives>
               </jats:inline-formula>. In particular, we characterize the soluble groups having a unique minimal family with this property (Theorem 2.3, Remark 2.4). In the case when <jats:inline-formula id="j_jgth-2017-0033_ineq_9998">
                  <jats:alternatives>
                     
                     <jats:inline-graphic xlink:href="graphic/j_jgth-2017-0033_eq_mi301.png" />
                     <jats:tex-math>{\Phi(G)=1}</jats:tex-math>
                  </jats:alternatives>
               </jats:inline-formula>, these are exactly the soluble groups in which each abelian normal subgroup has a unique conjugacy class of complements.</jats:p>
title: Critical maximal subgroups and conjugacy of supplements in finite soluble groups

items.abstract: <jats:p>Unification in Description Logics (DLs) has been proposed as an inference</jats:p><jats:p>service that can, for example, be used to detect redundancies in ontologies.</jats:p><jats:p>For the DL EL, which is used to define several large</jats:p><jats:p>biomedical ontologies, unification is NP-complete. However, the unification algorithms for EL developed</jats:p><jats:p>until recently could not deal with ontologies containing general concept inclusions (GCIs).</jats:p><jats:p>In a series of recent papers we have made some progress towards addressing this problem, but the ontologies the</jats:p><jats:p>developed unification algorithms can deal with need to satisfy a certain cycle restriction.</jats:p><jats:p>In the present paper, we follow a different approach.  Instead of restricting the input ontologies,</jats:p><jats:p>we generalize the notion of unifiers to so-called hybrid unifiers. Whereas classical unifiers can be viewed as acyclic TBoxes,</jats:p><jats:p>hybrid unifiers are cyclic TBoxes, which are interpreted together with the ontology of the input using a hybrid semantics that</jats:p><jats:p>combines fixpoint and declarative semantics. We show that hybrid unification in EL is NP-complete</jats:p>
title: Hybrid Unification in the Description Logic EL
